<subSubSection id="27285C1C6F2D4B404FE6F202FF026F2C" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" type="comments">
<paragraph id="AB9EDBF92F814FCFCD114CAC92052D5E" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Comment.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B70600DAB81D692A6A6FEF0A1D05248E" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">
This taxon was first described from the Chilean Altiplano and was found mixed with the nominate variety 
<taxonomicName id="779CB56A3222869B3C62B8291D4F3DE9" authority="" authorityName="E.A.Morales &amp; Vis" authorityYear="2007" class="Fragilariophyceae" family="Fragilariaceae" genus="Pseudostaurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pseudostaurosira laucensis" order="Fragilariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="laucensis">
<emphasis id="40B9CF41A90340A0C006D2FB76CF67BB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Pseudostaurosira laucensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lange-Bertalot &amp; Rumrich) E. Morales &amp; Vis (in 
<bibRefCitation id="4B422A5EDFA8260028089C03C2C61F83" author="Rumrich, U" journalOrPublisher="Iconographia Diatomologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 649" refId="B103" refString="Rumrich, U, Lange-Bertalot, H, Rumrich, M, 2000. Diatoms of the Andes. From Venezuela to Patagonia/Tierra del Fuego. Iconographia Diatomologica 9: 1 - 649" title="Diatoms of the Andes. From Venezuela to Patagonia / Tierra del Fuego." volume="9" year="2000">Rumrich et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
, p. 222, figs 10-20, 22, 23; 
<bibRefCitation id="AC8593B39B1147FB704F2BE91A2FA18C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1635/0097-3157(2007)156[123:EDBFCF]2.0.CO;2" author="Morales, EA" journalOrPublisher="Diatom Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" refId="B72" refString="Morales, EA, Vis, ML, 2007. Epilithic diatoms (Bacillariophyceae) from cloud forest and alpine streams in Bolivia, South America. Proceedings. Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 156(1): 123-155. https://doi.org/10.1635/0097-3157(2007)156[123:EDBFCF]2.0.CO;2" title="Epilithic diatoms (Bacillariophyceae) from cloud forest and alpine streams in Bolivia, South America. Proceedings. Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 156 (1): 123 - 155." url="https://doi.org/10.1635/0097-3157(2007)156[123:EDBFCF]2.0.CO;2" year="2007">Morales and Vis 2007</bibRefCitation>
, p. 25). This was the probable reason why Lange-Bertalot and Rumrich (in 
<bibRefCitation id="0051F326AF275FEB202816025F153F16" author="Rumrich, U" journalOrPublisher="Iconographia Diatomologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 649" refId="B103" refString="Rumrich, U, Lange-Bertalot, H, Rumrich, M, 2000. Diatoms of the Andes. From Venezuela to Patagonia/Tierra del Fuego. Iconographia Diatomologica 9: 1 - 649" title="Diatoms of the Andes. From Venezuela to Patagonia / Tierra del Fuego." volume="9" year="2000">Rumrich et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
) decided to describe it as a variety. However, we found the 
<taxonomicName id="822A58EE2359BFEA5117A4A429132285" authority="" authorityName="" class="Fragilariophyceae" family="Fragilariaceae" genus="Pseudostaurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pseudostaurosira laucensis subsp. var. var. vulpina" order="Fragilariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="laucensis" subSpecies="var." variety="vulpina">Pseudostaurosira laucensis var. vulpina</taxonomicName>
isolated from the nominate variety in the Desaguadero River sample. This population, like the one reported from Chile, exhibits a range of sizes which is probably showing that it is undergoing asexual reproduction and its size is most probably being re-established through sexual reproduction.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F245572038D9809DAA192728B06CCE1" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">
At the LM level, this taxon is distinguished by its typical triradiate shape (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D04AB5ECE77145B421CE05FA85A5911D" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. A-V LM images of little known and new &quot; araphid &quot; diatoms from the Bolivian Altiplano A-D Pseudostaurosira vulpina stat. nov. E-I P. frankenae sp. nov. (Fig. 6 E is the holotype) J-O P. occulta sp. nov. (Fig. 6 K corresponds to the holotype) P-V P. oblonga sp. nov. (Fig. 6 R corresponds to the holotype). Scale bar: 10 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622443" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">6A-D</figureCitation>
). Between each of the arms there is also a central inflation that becomes more pronounced as the valve decreases in size (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1BECDB60757EECA2877F06B9947ECF1A" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. A-V LM images of little known and new &quot; araphid &quot; diatoms from the Bolivian Altiplano A-D Pseudostaurosira vulpina stat. nov. E-I P. frankenae sp. nov. (Fig. 6 E is the holotype) J-O P. occulta sp. nov. (Fig. 6 K corresponds to the holotype) P-V P. oblonga sp. nov. (Fig. 6 R corresponds to the holotype). Scale bar: 10 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622443" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">6C, D</figureCitation>
). At the SEM level, the axial area is depressed in external view with respect to the virgae, while internally it is at the same level as the latter. Each of the arms has an apical pore field that lies within a shallow, irregular depression (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="05745E3D0ED05B616C7421839DC944D7" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. A-F SEM images of Pseudostaurosira vulpina sp. nov. A, B valve views showing striation pattern, features of the axial area, spine position and presence of depressed apical pore fields (black arrows) C, D close-ups with details of apical pore fields areolae and spines E tilted view of a frustule showing open girdle bands with overlapping extremes (white arrows) F internal view showing apical pore fields and the internal disk-like areolar depositions. Scale bars: 2 µm (C, D); 5 µm (A, B, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622444" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">7A-C</figureCitation>
) and opens to the valve interior as a plain plate of pores (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D88A6209C7EB3300D7093EAA6E2BB994" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. A-F SEM images of Pseudostaurosira vulpina sp. nov. A, B valve views showing striation pattern, features of the axial area, spine position and presence of depressed apical pore fields (black arrows) C, D close-ups with details of apical pore fields areolae and spines E tilted view of a frustule showing open girdle bands with overlapping extremes (white arrows) F internal view showing apical pore fields and the internal disk-like areolar depositions. Scale bars: 2 µm (C, D); 5 µm (A, B, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622444" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">7F</figureCitation>
). The transapically elongate areolae bear well-developed volae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="3A11067315FF5161B0FC21F252C7A3EF" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. A-F SEM images of Pseudostaurosira vulpina sp. nov. A, B valve views showing striation pattern, features of the axial area, spine position and presence of depressed apical pore fields (black arrows) C, D close-ups with details of apical pore fields areolae and spines E tilted view of a frustule showing open girdle bands with overlapping extremes (white arrows) F internal view showing apical pore fields and the internal disk-like areolar depositions. Scale bars: 2 µm (C, D); 5 µm (A, B, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622444" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">7A-E</figureCitation>
), which allow inorganic deposition of an inverted cone-like structure internally covering the areolae, sometimes filled with extra depositions in their hollow interior (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B4A162662C90E32BB971515061A1B66E" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. A-F SEM images of Pseudostaurosira vulpina sp. nov. A, B valve views showing striation pattern, features of the axial area, spine position and presence of depressed apical pore fields (black arrows) C, D close-ups with details of apical pore fields areolae and spines E tilted view of a frustule showing open girdle bands with overlapping extremes (white arrows) F internal view showing apical pore fields and the internal disk-like areolar depositions. Scale bars: 2 µm (C, D); 5 µm (A, B, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622444" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">7F</figureCitation>
). The spines are conical, but also it is common to find them as incipient, shapeless spines that are generated from the virgae and the vimines (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E46DA9F0646E9AD6CD36F6EB4442FC8F" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. A-F SEM images of Pseudostaurosira vulpina sp. nov. A, B valve views showing striation pattern, features of the axial area, spine position and presence of depressed apical pore fields (black arrows) C, D close-ups with details of apical pore fields areolae and spines E tilted view of a frustule showing open girdle bands with overlapping extremes (white arrows) F internal view showing apical pore fields and the internal disk-like areolar depositions. Scale bars: 2 µm (C, D); 5 µm (A, B, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622444" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">7E</figureCitation>
). The girdle elements vary in number, lack perforations and all are open (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A4E9A1288CF10D7089C7A81724CCA9A5" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. A-F SEM images of Pseudostaurosira vulpina sp. nov. A, B valve views showing striation pattern, features of the axial area, spine position and presence of depressed apical pore fields (black arrows) C, D close-ups with details of apical pore fields areolae and spines E tilted view of a frustule showing open girdle bands with overlapping extremes (white arrows) F internal view showing apical pore fields and the internal disk-like areolar depositions. Scale bars: 2 µm (C, D); 5 µm (A, B, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622444" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">7E</figureCitation>
). The valvocopula is wider. At the open side, each element has its terminations superimposing each other (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E8ABE75C58E7E10FB99AB84071FADA02" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. A-F SEM images of Pseudostaurosira vulpina sp. nov. A, B valve views showing striation pattern, features of the axial area, spine position and presence of depressed apical pore fields (black arrows) C, D close-ups with details of apical pore fields areolae and spines E tilted view of a frustule showing open girdle bands with overlapping extremes (white arrows) F internal view showing apical pore fields and the internal disk-like areolar depositions. Scale bars: 2 µm (C, D); 5 µm (A, B, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622444" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">7E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="FB1AF16793625F8F0A48AE11063797DF" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.187.73338.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/622443" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" start="Figure 6" startId="F6">
